## Usage

| Usage | (Number key) Shortcuts |
|---|---|
| 1. Set Checkpoints, Clip + VAE | (3) Checkpoint (subgraph) |
| 2. (optional) add LoRAs | (1) Settings, Prompt, Image, Video |
| 3. Enable Featuras you want with the "Features - Switch" | (1) Settings, Prompt, Image, Video |
| 4. Tune any parameter to your liking under "BASIC SETTINGS" | |
| 5. Add image you need | |
| 6. Write your prompts | (4) Samplers |
| 7. Enable as many samplers as you want the video going | |
| 8. Generate | |

nodes.title: Settiings and features
widgets_values:
## BASIC settings and features | Setting | Default / Example | Description | |---|---:|---| | **VAE** | same as WAN 2.1 | Still using the same VAE as WAN 2.1. | | **CLIP** | standard encoder | Use your preferred standard CLIP text encoder. No CLIP Vision H ‚Äî not trained/implemented in WAN 2.2 and weights are disabled. | | **CLIP device** | "cpu" or "default" | CLIP can be offloaded to CPU for VRAM savings ‚Üí device = "cpu". If VRAM is sufficient, use device = "default" for faster inference. | | **Checkpoint** | Safetensors/GGUf |Choose the type of Checkpoint to use. Wan 2.2 uses a different diffusion model for the first steps (high noise) vs the last steps (low noise). You can ether use safetensors or gguf.| | **LoRAs** | SVI | Every sampler need the SVI high+low LoRA. Add LoRAs to your liking for stylistic/behavioral tweaks. | | **Seed** | 40+ | Every sampler has set a fixed seed. Starting with 40 and +1 per sampler. | | **FPS** | 16 | Frames per second for videos. Use 24 for faster motion/shorter videos. | | **Frames** | 49‚Äì113 | Total frames determine video length. Examples: 3s=49, 4s=65, 5s=81, 6s=97, 7s=113. Math: (Seconds * 16) + 1 = total frames. | | **Feature switch** | off/on | Enable features you want to use. | | **CRF** | 30 | Video compression level. 30 is near-lossless (AV1). | | **Steps total** | 6 | Total steps - node handles step math. More steps ‚Üí higher quality but longer generation. Use even numbers. | | **Step Refiner** | 3 | Default 3 (50% of 6). Change to test different swap behavior. | | **CFG** | 1.0 | Controls prompt adherence. Use 1-1.5. 1 disables/ignores the negative prompt. 1.0 is needed for speed-up's like 4/8-step models/LoRAs | | **Sigma Shift** | 8 | Default 8. Adjust and test; WAN 2.2 valid in range 5‚Äì8. | | **Video resolution** | R3# | Scale to selected MP with automatic calculations. Affects sampling time, VRAM and RAM usage. | | **Upscale** | 2x | Final resolution = 2 √ó start resolution while maintaining aspect ratio. No morph; aspect-correct to optimal WAN resolution. | | **Positive prompt** | none | Write your positive prompt!
1) Brief description of the setting/appearance
2) Actions, motions, story
3) Camera composition
CFG 1 normally disables/ignores the negative prompt!| | **Interpolation** | off | This will interpolate your video to double fps at the end. Interpolated FPS = 2 √ó FPS. | | **Watermark** | off | Here you can set a watermark image and calibrate the settings to your liking. |

### üé• AV1 (WEBM) CRF Recommendations for WAN 2.2 --- | Purpose | CRF | Notes | |----------|-----|-------| | Master / Archival | 30 | Nearly lossless; best for grading or editing | | Balanced | 31‚Äì33 | Ideal quality-to-size balance | | Social | 34‚Äì37 | Lighter files, still decent | ### üé• H.265 (MP4) CRF Recommendations for WAN 2.2 --- | Purpose | CRF | Notes | |----------|-----|-------| | Master / Archival | 19 | Nearly lossless; best for grading or editing | | Balanced | 20‚Äì22 | Ideal quality-to-size balance | | Social | 23‚Äì25 | Lighter files, still decent | --- üí° *Tip* For AI-generated videos:
``` AV1 CRF 30 or H.265 CRF 19 ``` Extreme good results with minimal size. AV1 (WEBM) is superior for webcontent and quality.
H265 is in every way superior to H264. ---

nodes.title: Resolution note
widgets_values:
### Automatic scaling and resolution calculation The initial image will be scaled on optimized math targeting a WAN 2.2 VAE (div16) resolution. Aspect will be calculated automatically and the video resolution will be set to the nearest possible match with the megapixel count. | Stage | Target MP | Quality | Use case | |---:|---:|---:|---| | 1 | 0.25 | Fast Preview
~ 360p| Motion/physics tests. | | 2 | 0.40 | SD
~ 480p| "Sweet spot" for speed. | | 3 | 0.60 | SD+
~ 576p| Optimal for mobile-first content. | | 4 | 0.85 | HD
~ 720p| Very stable, crisp details. | | 5 | 1.05 | HD+
~ 768p| Maximum stability for Image-to-Video. | | 6 | 1.30 | HQ
~ 900p| High detail, very slow (Requires high VRAM). | | 7 | 2.07 | FHD
~ 1080p| Production grade detail, extreme slow (Requires very high VRAM). |
